LightRAG
LightRAG is a RAG system.

Gemini
Gemini is used by LightRAG to provide answers.

RAG System
A RAG system is a type of system.

Physiological Neonatal Jaundice
A common form of jaundice in newborns that typically appears after 24 hours, peaks between days 3-5, and resolves naturally after 7-10 days.

Newborn
An infant who can experience both physiological and pathological jaundice.

24 Hours
A critical time marker; physiological jaundice typically appears after this period, while jaundice appearing before this period may indicate a pathological condition.

Pathological Jaundice
A more serious type of jaundice in newborns that requires medical evaluation, indicated by early onset or prolonged duration.

More Than 14 Days
A duration of jaundice in newborns that, if persisted beyond, warrants evaluation for a pathological condition.

7-10 Days
The usual duration after which physiological neonatal jaundice resolves on its own.

Days 3-5
The typical timeframe during which physiological neonatal jaundice reaches its peak intensity.

Dangerous Signs
A collection of symptoms in newborns with jaundice that signal a need for medical assessment due to potential severity.

Poor Feeding
A symptom described as a dangerous sign when present in newborns with jaundice.

Fever
A symptom described as a dangerous sign when present in newborns with jaundice.

Lethargy
A symptom described as a dangerous sign when present in newborns with jaundice.

Convulsions
A symptom described as a dangerous sign when present in newborns with jaundice.
